Let me think through this step by step...

The key psychological mechanisms involved in responder behavior in this ultimatum game are fairness and self-interest.  Responders will likely consider the fairness of the offer relative to their contribution and the opponent's contribution, as well as the monetary gain they receive.  A purely self-interested responder would accept any positive offer. However,  research suggests that people often reject unfair offers, even if it means losing money, indicating a role for fairness considerations.

These mechanisms interact in a complex way. A highly self-interested responder would be more likely to accept even very unfair offers with high monetary value. In contrast, a responder highly concerned with fairness would be less likely to accept offers that deviate significantly from an equal split, regardless of the monetary value.  The relative weighting of self-interest versus fairness will vary between individuals.

A mathematical form capturing this interaction could be a weighted sum of self-interest (represented by the monetary gain) and a fairness term. The fairness term could be computed as the difference between the proposed split and an equitable split, where an equitable split is based on the relative contributions of tokens. The relative weight given to these two aspects can be represented by a parameter.

Two parameters are sufficient to capture this: one to represent the relative weight given to fairness versus self-interest and another one to represent the sensitivity to the degree of inequity.  

The model variables map to observable behavior as follows:  higher values of the self-interest parameter will lead to more acceptances, even for unfair offers. Higher values of the fairness parameter will lead to more rejections of offers that are perceived as unfair. The combination of these parameters determines the responder's acceptance threshold for a given offer.


